Case 1: Low-Load Emotional Stabilization System (LLES)

This model demonstrates how a stable mind architecture can maintain low-load operation in the chain:
	1.	Emotion arises (from an external trigger)
	2.	Attention expands or contracts (without forming a self-reinforcing loop)
	3.	Self-regulation remains foreground
	4.	Emotion naturally dissipates back into the experience layer

No expansion of meaning structures occurs. No value-narrative stacking.
Therefore, the system is safe and lightweight.

Applications:
	â€¢	Lightweight psychological tool
	â€¢	Attention-regulation training
	â€¢	Reducing short-term cognitive overload

